<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-538-382  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 538 382.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Digital Review  June 4 1990 v7 n22 p6(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Cahners-Ziff Publishing Associates LP 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Systems Union beefs up financial management software. (SystemsUnion announces updated version of international financialsoftware)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bowen, Ted Smalley.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Systems Union Inc introduces SunAccount 3.4, an updated version ofits financial management software designed for multinationalcorporations.andP;  SunAccount has English, French, Spanish, andJapanese versions, and it runs on VAX, IBM AS/400 and MS-DOSplatforms.andP;  The new version accommodates four Financial AccountingStandards Board reporting methods and provides relational DBMSaccess.andP;  Other features in SunSystems 3.4 include a naturallanguage macro processor called FreeFormat and interfaces toAccess Technology's 20/20 and Lotus' 1-2-3.andP;  Site licenses forSunAccount 3.4 range from $3,500 to $100,000 for a single-currencyversion and $6,000 to $100,000 for the multi-currency version.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Systems Union Inc. (product introduction).andO;Product:   SunAccount 3.4 (Financial software) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Financial SoftwareProduct IntroductionInternational Trade.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Systems Union beefs up financial management softwareandM;NEW YORK -- Systems Union, the American subsidiary of Systems Union Group ofLondon, has announced an updated version of its multilanguage, multicurrencyfinancial management software.andM;SunAccount is the core module of Systems Union's SunSystems, a series offinancial management packages designed for multinational businesses requiringreporting and data exchange between central sites and internationalsubsidiaries.andP;  The program has English, French, Spanish and Japaneseversions.andM;SunSystems runs on VAXes, IBM AS/400s and MS-DOS PCs.andM;&quot;We design products for use in organizations [that] require distributedsolutions throughout international offices,&quot; said Systems Union Senior VicePresident Robin Morris.andM;SunAccount version 3.4 includes hierarchical reporting capabilities andexpanded handling of Financial Accounting Standards Board (FASB) standards,according to Morris.andM;SunAccount 3.4 accommodates four FASB reporting methods, whereas previousreleases supported only one.andM;SunAccount also provides RDBMS access, which is increasingly important in thefinancial software arena.andP;  (See &quot;Financial software rivalries heat up,&quot; DR,May 28, page 1.)andP;  SunSystems currently provides an interface to Oracle onVMS, and Systems Union is beta-testing a version that supports Ingres.andO;Systems Union is also a participant in Synergy, Sybase's third-partydevelopment program, Morris said.andM;SunAccount 3.4 also has interfaces to Lotus' 1-2-3, Access Technology's 20/20and other third-party applications.andM;SunSystems also includes a natural-language-macro processor, FreeFormat, forwriting routine commands.andP;  The natural language processor is designed toallow executives to query the financial system without the aid of a systemmanager.andM;SunAccount is available now.andP;  Site licenses are priced from $3,500 to$100,000 for the single-currency version and from $6,000 to $100,000 for themulticurrency version.andM;Systems Union Inc. can be contacted at 244 E. 48th St., New York, NY 10017,(212) 743-7777.andO;</TEXT></DOC>